From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 A reduced form of a synthetic hydrogen-assembled molecular shuttle for nano-technological applications has been investigated by molecular dynamics simulations and density functional theory calculations. It is composed by a benzylic amide macrocycle mechanically locked onto a thread in acetonitrile solution. Classical sampling indicates, in agreement with experimental findings, that in equilibrium condition at 298 K the macrocycle and the naphthalimide radical anion moiety within the thread strongly interact forming four strong OCN–H–OCNR hydrogen bonds. Simulations also revealed that the geometry of the supramolecular assembly reversibly oscillates between unfolded and folded conformations, with the latter characterized by an electrostatic hook involving the succinamide end group and the macrocycle itself. Finally, the simulated UV-Vis absorption spectra for free and complexed reduced naphthalimide quantitatively confirm that the transient spectroscopic change experimentally used as a probe for monitoring the translational motion of the macrocycle, from succinamide to naphthalimide stations, accompanying the selective electrochemical reduction.
From Soup: 1 A reduced form of a synthetic hydrogen-assembled molecular shuttle for nano-technological applications has been investigated by molecular dynamics simulations and density functional theory calculations. It is composed by a benzylic amide macrocycle mechanically locked onto a thread in acetonitrile solution. Classical sampling indicates, in agreement with experimental findings, that in equilibrium condition at 298 K the macrocycle and the naphthalimide radical anion moiety within the thread strongly interact forming four strong OCN–H–O CNR hydrogen bonds. Simulations also revealed that the geometry of the supramolecular assembly reversibly oscillates between unfolded and folded conformations, with the latter characterized by an electrostatic hook involving the succinamide end group and the macrocycle itself. Finally, the simulated UV-Vis absorption spectra for free and complexed reduced naphthalimide quantitatively confirm that the transient spectroscopic change experimentally used as a probe for monitoring the translational motion of the macrocycle , from succinamide to naphthalimide stations, accompanying the selective electrochemical reduction .
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Miniaturization, design and synthesis of multicomponent molecular devices at nanoscale dimensions is one of the most challenging research areas in modern science. Inspired by the ability of some biological systems in nature, such as ATP synthase,1 Titin (also known as Connectin)2 or Myosin,3 to efficiently convert chemical energy into molecular movements, various types of artificial molecular devices and machines4 have been developed in recent decades such as molecular switches,5 elevators,6 valves,7 rotors,8 propellers,9 walkers,10 springs,11 and shuttles.12,13 Many interesting strategies and concepts concerning the control of molecular-level movements by external inputs (chemical reagents, pH-variation, electrochemical reduction, UV-Vis radiation) have been successfully addressed by different research groups. The basic feature which enables a molecule to mimic functions of a macroscopic machinery, usually resides in the ability of certain nano-scale “objects” to funnel an ad hoc external perturbation in controlled conformational rearrangements. For example, in a very recent application Feringa and co-workers reported that a light-driven molecular rotor may also be chemically blocked by external signals (i.e. an acid/base triggered variation of the protonation state of an ammonium group in a “rotating arm”).14
From Soup: 2 Miniaturization, design and synthesis of multicomponent molecular devices at nanoscale dimensions is one of the most challenging research areas in modern science. Inspired by the ability of some biological systems in nature, such as ATP synthase, 1 Titin (also known as Connectin) 2 or Myosin, 3 to efficiently convert chemical energy into molecular movements, various types of artificial molecular devices and machines 4 have been developed in recent decades such as molecular switches, 5 elevators, 6 valves, 7 rotors, 8 propellers, 9 walkers, 10 springs, 11 and shuttles. 12,13 Many interesting strategies and concepts concerning the control of molecular-level movements by external inputs (chemical reagents, pH-variation, electrochemical reduction , UV-Vis radiation) have been successfully addressed by different research groups. The basic feature which enables a molecule to mimic functions of a macroscopic machinery, usually resides in the ability of certain nano-scale “objects” to funnel an ad hoc external perturbation in controlled conformational rearrangements. For example, in a very recent application Feringa and co-workers reported that a light-driven molecular rotor may also be chemically blocked by external signals ( i.e. an acid/base triggered variation of the protonation state of an ammonium group in a “rotating arm”). 14
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 Recently, several experiments have also suggested that the solvent may heavily influence the conformational flexibility of molecular devices and machines, thus affecting in many cases the active stimuli-responsive submolecular motions.15 Following the huge amount of exciting experimental data in recent years, the necessity of a rigorous theoretical/computational modelling for initiating a rational design and synthesis of molecular-based machineries of increasing efficiency has been emerging. Obviously, any serious modelling must necessarily maintain the intrinsic configurational complexity of these molecular systems.
From Soup: 3 Recently, several experiments have also suggested that the solvent may heavily influence the conformational flexibility of molecular devices and machines, thus affecting in many cases the active stimuli-responsive submolecular motions. 15 Following the huge amount of exciting experimental data in recent years, the necessity of a rigorous theoretical/computational modelling for initiating a rational design and synthesis of molecular-based machineries of increasing efficiency has been emerging. Obviously, any serious modelling must necessarily maintain the intrinsic configurational complexity of these molecular systems.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 A certain number of research papers, in this respect, are now available in the literature combining experiments and first-principles simulations. For example, in a very recent paper Leigh and coworkers, also by means of Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulations, have successfully addressed a succinamide-based molecular thread interacting with a benzylic amide macrocycle in an organic rotaxane framework in solution;16 in particular, in this work the authors have restated, one more time, the intimate correlation between conformational shaping and supramolecular interactions in mechanically locked assemblies designed to achieve specific signal-triggered functions.
From Soup: 4 A certain number of research papers, in this respect, are now available in the literature combining experiments and first-principles simulations. For example, in a very recent paper Leigh and coworkers, also by means of Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulations, have successfully addressed a succinamide-based molecular thread interacting with a benzylic amide macrocycle in an organic rotaxane framework in solution; 16 in particular, in this work the authors have restated, one more time, the intimate correlation between conformational shaping and supramolecular interactions in mechanically locked assemblies designed to achieve specific signal-triggered functions.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 In recent years, part of our efforts have been focussed on this fascinating research area with some computational investigations concerning the thermodynamics17 and kinetics18 of an electrochemically-driven conformational switching mechanism occurring in a synthetic thread in solution. The thread we studied was previously reported in the literature as a molecular component of a fast and reversible hydrogen-bonded molecular shuttle13 consisting of a succinamide (succ) chemical group, a C12 alkyl-spacer and a 3,6-di-tert-butyl-1,8-naphthalimide (ni) moiety, see Fig. 1a. Our simulations were able to suggest that such a thread, even though originally designed to be involved in a more complex device, may efficiently work in solution as a tens of nanoseconds time scale two-states molecular switch under electrochemical control.17,18 Note that, in analogy with the work accomplished by Brouwer et al.,13 in our computational setup we were assuming the same external stimulus (i.e.reduction/oxidation of ni) but we completely disregarded the presence of the macrocycle (see Fig. 1b).
From Soup: 5 In recent years, part of our efforts have been focussed on this fascinating research area with some computational investigations concerning the thermodynamics 17 and kinetics 18 of an electrochemically-driven conformational switching mechanism occurring in a synthetic thread in solution. The thread we studied was previously reported in the literature as a molecular component of a fast and reversible hydrogen-bonded molecular shuttle 13 consisting of a succinamide ( succ ) chemical group, a C 12 alkyl-spacer and a 3,6-di- tert -butyl-1,8-naphthalimide ( ni ) moiety, see Fig. 1a . Our simulations were able to suggest that such a thread, even though originally designed to be involved in a more complex device, may efficiently work in solution as a tens of nanoseconds time scale two-states molecular switch under electrochemical control. 17,18 Note that, in analogy with the work accomplished by Brouwer et al. , 13 in our computational setup we were assuming the same external stimulus ( i.e. reduction/oxidation of ni ) but we completely disregarded the presence of the macrocycle (see Fig. 1b ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 As a continuation of such a research work, in the present paper we report a computational study dealing with the hydrogen-assembled molecular rotaxane reported in ref. 13. In particular, we investigated its reduced form at equilibrium conditions in which, on the basis of experimental evidences, the naphthalimide is present as the radical anion and surrounded by the benzylic amide macrocycle (bam). With the precise aim of analyzing the existence of the H-bonding motif, which is supposed to be the non-covalent driving force behind the shuttling process (from succ to ni−) of the macrocycle upon electrochemical reduction,13 we have carried out a 0.1 microseconds molecular dynamics simulations starting from the rotaxane in the conformation as reported in Fig. 1b. Hence, the position of the macrocycle along the thread as well as the electrostatic interactions with succ and ni− stations are then investigated. Some insights about the conformational flexibility of the overall supramolecular assembly will be also reported. Finally, the photoabsorption spectra of ni− and ni−/bam interacting couple have been estimated by means of Conductor-like Polarizable Continuum Method (CPCM)19 and Time-Dependent Density Functional Theory (TD-DFT) calculations.20 This enabled us to: (i) investigate the effects of noncovalent interactions on the UV-Vis absorption maxima characteristic of the naphthalimide radical anion; (ii) compare the variation of the calculated absorption peak (at around 415 nm) with the experimentally proposed one suggested to provide a direct measure of the relative position of the macrocycle with respect to the succ and ni− stations.13
From Soup: 6 As a continuation of such a research work, in the present paper we report a computational study dealing with the hydrogen-assembled molecular rotaxane reported in ref. 13 . In particular, we investigated its reduced form at equilibrium conditions in which, on the basis of experimental evidences, the naphthalimide is present as the radical anion and surrounded by the benzylic amide macrocycle ( bam ). With the precise aim of analyzing the existence of the H-bonding motif, which is supposed to be the non-covalent driving force behind the shuttling process (from succ to ni − ) of the macrocycle upon electrochemical reduction , 13 we have carried out a 0.1 microseconds molecular dynamics simulations starting from the rotaxane in the conformation as reported in Fig. 1b . Hence, the position of the macrocycle along the thread as well as the electrostatic interactions with succ and ni − stations are then investigated. Some insights about the conformational flexibility of the overall supramolecular assembly will be also reported. Finally, the photoabsorption spectra of ni − and ni − / bam interacting couple have been estimated by means of Conductor-like Polarizable Continuum Method (CPCM) 19 and Time-Dependent Density Functional Theory (TD-DFT) calculations. 20 This enabled us to: (i) investigate the effects of noncovalent interactions on the UV-Vis absorption maxima characteristic of the naphthalimide radical anion ; (ii) compare the variation of the calculated absorption peak (at around 415 nm) with the experimentally proposed one suggested to provide a direct measure of the relative position of the macrocycle with respect to the succ and ni − stations. 13
