From cou.: 10 The conformational flexibility in solution of the synthetic rotaxane depicted in Fig. 1b during the explored time range has been characterized by monitoring the position and the relative orientation of the macrocycle along the thread. Particular attention was also given to the mechanical behaviour of the succ–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni artificial thread. To this end, inspired by our recent works,17,18 we dumped along the 100 ns MD simulation the distance between the geometrical centres of the three main internal groups that are the succ and ni− stations, and the mechanically locked benzylic amide macrocycle (see Fig. 1b). Thus, the trajectories of the inter-moieties (i.e. succ-ni−, succ-bam and bam–ni−) distances along the simulation as well as the emerged normalized probability distributions have been calculated and discussed. The time evolution of these set of internal variables allowed us to point out two basic structural features of the currently investigated rotaxane: (i) the deviation (if any) of the molecular thread from a conformational basin in which it is assumed to be found in a fully elongated structure (as for example implicitly reported in Fig. 1b), and (ii) the position of the macrocycle with respect to the ni− H-bonded acceptor unit. This may be viewed as an interesting structural parameter to be compared with experimental data supporting the existence of a strong electrostatic glue which has the effect to confine the bamgroup around the reduced moiety.13
From Soup: 10 The conformational flexibility in solution of the synthetic rotaxane depicted in Fig. 1b during the explored time range has been characterized by monitoring the position and the relative orientation of the macrocycle along the thread. Particular attention was also given to the mechanical behaviour of the succ –[C 12 alkyl spacer]– ni artificial thread. To this end, inspired by our recent works, 17,18 we dumped along the 100 ns MD simulation the distance between the geometrical centres of the three main internal groups that are the succ and ni − stations, and the mechanically locked benzylic amide macrocycle (see Fig. 1b ). Thus, the trajectories of the inter-moieties ( i.e. succ - ni − , succ - bam and bam – ni − ) distances along the simulation as well as the emerged normalized probability distributions have been calculated and discussed. The time evolution of these set of internal variables allowed us to point out two basic structural features of the currently investigated rotaxane : (i) the deviation (if any) of the molecular thread from a conformational basin in which it is assumed to be found in a fully elongated structure (as for example implicitly reported in Fig. 1b ), and (ii) the position of the macrocycle with respect to the ni − H-bonded acceptor unit. This may be viewed as an interesting structural parameter to be compared with experimental data supporting the existence of a strong electrostatic glue which has the effect to confine the bam group around the reduced moiety. 13
