From cou.: 31 It should be pertinent to underline that, in the present investigation, we are not interested in reproducing exactly the absolute value of such a main band which may be viewed as systematically affected by the employed functional; rather, during our simulations we decided to choose as ‘observable’ the experimental excitation wavelength shift (from 415 nm to 411 nm, Δλmax = 4 nm) which was originally proposed as a crucial variable for: (i) establishing the position of the macrocycle along the reduced succ–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni− thread; and (ii) obtaining information about the relaxation times accompanying the shuttling movement in different solvents of increased polarity.13 In this respect, the data collected in Table 1 reveal that either the TD-UPBE0 or TD-UPW91 estimation of the absorption shift (termed as Δλmax) had success in reproducing the energy change observed in laboratory. In particular, the Δλmax term calculated at TD-UPW91 perfectly agrees with the experiments, while the TD-UPBE0 value is seen to be a little bit overestimated (Δλmax = 5.5 nm, see Table 1). The computed shifts are found to be in the right direction and, most importantly, qualitatively confirm the fact that the shorter excitation wavelength absorption of the naphthalimide radical anion is strictly linked to the formation of a cooperative electrostatic network composed by four [bam-side]OCN–H–OCNR[ni-side] hydrogen bonding interactions.13 Always in this context, in a recent application dealing with such a synthetic thread in solution,18 we estimated that when the local polarity of the environment in proximity of the naphthalimide chemical group is increased for the presence of an explicit [succ-side]OCN–H–OCNR[ni-side] noncovalent interaction, the excitation absorption wavelength at 415 nm undergoes a blue shift of 1.5 nm. It is therefore clear that the naphthalimide moiety in such a synthetic rotaxane working in solution can be considered as a sort of essential “residue” which provides both a site for the selective reduction triggering the electromechanical response, and a visible (violet) warning light through which obtaining information about the current status of the relative position of the ring while approaching to the ni moiety (see Fig. 8).
From Soup: 31 The two functionals employed in our investigation show a different intensity pattern with the hybrid PBE0 featuring higher oscillator strengths than those computed taking into account the PW91 one (see Table 1 ). We also note that they provide comparable oscillator strengths both in the presence and in the absence of the benzylic amide macrocycle . Unfortunately, the computed intensity at TD-UDFT level cannot be compared with available experimental data , because the electronic absorption spectra of electrochemically generated succ –[C 12 alkyl spacer]– ni − thread and the related rotaxane are always normalized in terms to the most intense absorption peak falling around 415/410 nm (see for example Fig. 3 reported in ref. 13 ). Finally, in our model systems in solution we replaced the (3,6) tert -butyl groups in the experimentally investigated naphthalimide with methyl groups only having first realized that such a substitution had shown a negligible effect on the strongest 2 π → π* electronic transition (the separation between the two absorption maxima remains confined within a single nanometre).
 ###### 
From cou.: 32 The two functionals employed in our investigation show a different intensity pattern with the hybrid PBE0 featuring higher oscillator strengths than those computed taking into account the PW91 one (see Table 1). We also note that they provide comparable oscillator strengths both in the presence and in the absence of the benzylic amide macrocycle. Unfortunately, the computed intensity at TD-UDFT level cannot be compared with available experimental data, because the electronic absorption spectra of electrochemically generated succ–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni− thread and the related rotaxane are always normalized in terms to the most intense absorption peak falling around 415/410 nm (see for example Fig. 3 reported in ref. 13). Finally, in our model systems in solution we replaced the (3,6)tert-butyl groups in the experimentally investigated naphthalimide with methyl groups only having first realized that such a substitution had shown a negligible effect on the strongest 2π → π* electronic transition (the separation between the two absorption maxima remains confined within a single nanometre).
From Soup: 32 Summarizing, simulations dealing with a hydrogen-bonded molecular shuttle in a reduced form in its actual conditions— acetonitrile dilute solution, 298 K—are here reported. MD simulation is combined with TD-DFT/C-PCM computations in an attempt to computationally address the conformational shaping in solution of such a nanoscale machine, as well as a characteristic UV-Vis absorption signal used to detect the shuttling movements of a benzylic amide macrocycle mechanically trapped onto the succ –[C 12 alkyl spacer]– ni − thread. Our results provide both a computational point of view supporting experimental observations and some insights into the mechanical and electronic properties of the succ –[C 12 alkyl spacer]– ni − / bam system in solution. MD clearly evidences the crucial role played by noncovalent forces coupled with thermal effects in the investigated rotaxane which shows, at least within the range explored, a reversible folding/elongation-like conformational transition occurring in the flexible succ -–[C 12 alkyl spacer]– ni − thread in the reduced ensemble. As far as folded conformations are concerned, the benzylic amide macrocycle in its neutral form is seen to interact by means of electrostatic forces not only with the reduced naphthalimide station, but also with the succinamide end group. In agreement with experimental measurements, we observe that during the MD simulation the reduced molecular device shows a ring which lies completely towards the radical anion unit; this implies, as suggested by experiments, the presence of a peculiar electrostatic glue connecting the two molecular components ( i.e. bam and ni − ) in the supramolecular assembly through the formation of four OCN–H–O CNR hydrogen bonding contacts. It is worth noting that supramolecular interactions holding the succ and bam moieties at H-bond distance between them were not taken into account in the original experimental framework which mainly focussed the attention on the description of the shuttling movement along the thread. Quantum-chemical calculations carried out on a model compound embedded in a continuum and polarizable media suggest that supramolecular forces while keeping the bam and ni − molecular systems close to each other modulate the optical response of the chromophore making the shuttling movement visible as elegantly reported in the experiments.
 ###### 
From cou.: 33 Summarizing, simulations dealing with a hydrogen-bonded molecular shuttle in a reduced form in its actual conditions—acetonitrile dilute solution, 298 K—are here reported. MD simulation is combined with TD-DFT/C-PCM computations in an attempt to computationally address the conformational shaping in solution of such a nanoscale machine, as well as a characteristic UV-Vis absorption signal used to detect the shuttling movements of a benzylic amide macrocycle mechanically trapped onto the succ–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni− thread. Our results provide both a computational point of view supporting experimental observations and some insights into the mechanical and electronic properties of the succ–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni−/bam system in solution. MD clearly evidences the crucial role played by noncovalent forces coupled with thermal effects in the investigated rotaxane which shows, at least within the range explored, a reversible folding/elongation-like conformational transition occurring in the flexible succ-–[C12 alkyl spacer]–ni− thread in the reduced ensemble. As far as folded conformations are concerned, the benzylic amide macrocycle in its neutral form is seen to interact by means of electrostatic forces not only with the reduced naphthalimide station, but also with the succinamide end group. In agreement with experimental measurements, we observe that during the MD simulation the reduced molecular device shows a ring which lies completely towards the radical anion unit; this implies, as suggested by experiments, the presence of a peculiar electrostatic glue connecting the two molecular components (i.e. bam and ni−) in the supramolecular assembly through the formation of four OCN–H–OCNR hydrogen bonding contacts. It is worth noting that supramolecular interactions holding the succ and bam moieties at H-bond distance between them were not taken into account in the original experimental framework which mainly focussed the attention on the description of the shuttling movement along the thread. Quantum-chemical calculations carried out on a model compound embedded in a continuum and polarizable media suggest that supramolecular forces while keeping the bam and ni− molecular systems close to each other modulate the optical response of the chromophore making the shuttling movement visible as elegantly reported in the experiments.
